{"title":"Series and convergence","markdown":{"yaml":{"title":"Series and convergence"},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\nA necessary condition for convergence of a series is that the underlying sequence must have a limit 0. \n\n::: {#thm-conv}\n**(Necessary condition for convergence).**\n\nIf $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty a_n$ converges, then $\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} a_n=0$.\n:::\n\n::: {.callout-tip collapse=\"true\" title=\"Proof\"}\nLet $s_n=\\sum_{k=0}^n a_k$. If $s_n\\to S$, then also $s_{n+1}\\to S$. Hence\n$$\na_{n+1}=s_{n+1}-s_n \\longrightarrow S-S = 0.\n$$\n:::\n\nFurther basic properties of series are these algebraic ones. You may try to prove them yourself:\n\n::: {#thm-linear}\n**(Linearity of convergent series).**\n\nLet $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty a_n$ and $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty b_n$ converge with sums $S_a$ and $S_b$.\nThen for any $c\\in\\mathbb{R}$:\n\n1. $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (c a_n)$ converges and has sum $cS_a$;\n2. $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (a_n\\pm b_n)$ converges and has sum $S_a\\pm S_b$.\n\n:::\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":"\nA necessary condition for convergence of a series is that the underlying sequence must have a limit 0. \n\n::: {#thm-conv}\n**(Necessary condition for convergence).**\n\nIf $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty a_n$ converges, then $\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} a_n=0$.\n:::\n\n::: {.callout-tip collapse=\"true\" title=\"Proof\"}\nLet $s_n=\\sum_{k=0}^n a_k$. If $s_n\\to S$, then also $s_{n+1}\\to S$. Hence\n$$\na_{n+1}=s_{n+1}-s_n \\longrightarrow S-S = 0.\n$$\n:::\n\nFurther basic properties of series are these algebraic ones. You may try to prove them yourself:\n\n::: {#thm-linear}\n**(Linearity of convergent series).**\n\nLet $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty a_n$ and $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty b_n$ converge with sums $S_a$ and $S_b$.\nThen for any $c\\in\\mathbb{R}$:\n\n1. $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (c a_n)$ converges and has sum $cS_a$;\n2. $\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (a_n\\pm b_n)$ converges and has sum $S_a\\pm S_b$.\n\n:::\n"},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":